        <exercise>
            <title>Homogeneous Equations</title>
            <statement>
                <p>A first-order differential equation, <m>y' = f(x, y)</m>, is <em>homogeneous</em> if <m>f(x, y) = f(tx, ty)</m>.
                    <ol>

                        <li><p>Show that the equation
                            <md>\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{x^2 + y^2}{2xy}</md>
                        is homogeneous.</p></li>

                        <li><p>Let <m>y = xv</m> and show that the equation in part (a) can be written as
                            <md>v + x\frac{dv}{dx} = \frac{x^2 + v^2 x^2}{2v x^2}.</md>
                        Use the fact that this new equation is separable to solve for <m>y</m>.</p></li>

                        <li><p>Show that any homogeneous equation <m>y' = f(x, y)</m> can be transformed into a separable differential equation by making the substitution <m>y = vx</m>.</p></li>

                        <li><p>A function <m>f</m> is said to homogeneous of degree <m>n</m> if <m>f(t x, t y)= t^n f(x, y)</m> for <m>n = 1, 2, \ldots</m>. Show that differential equation
                            <md>P(x, y) dx + Q(x, y) dy = 0,</md>
                        where <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are both homogeneous of degree <m>n</m>, 
                        can be transformed into a separable differential equation using the substitution <m>y = vx</m>.</p></li>

                        <li><p>Solve the differential equation
                            <md>x^2 y' = 2 y^2 - x^2.</md></p></li>


                        <li><p>Solve the differential equation
                            <md>y' = \frac{2y^4 + x^4}{xy^3}.</md></p></li>

                    </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution component="instructors">
            <ol>
                <li>
                <p>Let</p>
                <md>f(x,y)=\frac{x^2+y^2}{2xy}.</md>
                <p>Then for any nonzero constant <m>t</m>,</p>
                <md>
                    f(tx,ty)=\frac{(tx)^2+(ty)^2}{2(tx)(ty)}
                    =\frac{t^2(x^2+y^2)}{2t^2xy}
                    =\frac{x^2+y^2}{2xy}
                    =f(x,y).
                </md>
                <p>Hence the differential equation is homogeneous.</p>
                </li>

                <li>
                <p>With the substitution <m>y=xv</m>, we have <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=v+x\dfrac{dv}{dx}</m>. Substituting into the differential equation gives</p>
                <md>
                    v+x\frac{dv}{dx}
                    =\frac{x^2+(vx)^2}{2x(vx)}
                    =\frac{x^2+v^2x^2}{2vx^2}.
                </md>
                <p>Canceling <m>x^2</m> yields</p>
                <md>v+x\frac{dv}{dx}=\frac{1+v^2}{2v},</md>
                <p>so</p>
                <md>
                    x\frac{dv}{dx}=\frac{1+v^2}{2v}-v=\frac{1-v^2}{2v}.
                </md>
                <p>This is separable:</p>
                <md>\frac{2v}{1-v^2}\,dv=\frac{dx}{x}.</md>
                <p>Integrating, let <m>u=1-v^2</m>, <m>du=-2v\,dv</m>, to obtain</p>
                <md>
                    -\ln|1-v^2|=\ln|x|+C.
                </md>
                <p>Equivalently, <m>\ln|1-v^2|=-\ln|x|+C</m>, so <m>1-v^2=\dfrac{C}{x}</m>. Since <m>v=\dfrac{y}{x}</m>, we get</p>
                <md>
                    1-\left(\frac{y}{x}\right)^2=\frac{C}{x}
                    \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
                    y^2=x^2+Cx.
                </md>
                </li>

                <li>
                <p>If <m>y'=f(x,y)</m> is homogeneous, then for <m>x\neq 0</m> we may take <m>t=\dfrac{1}{x}</m> to get</p>
                <md>
                    f(x,y)=f\!\left(1,\frac{y}{x}\right).
                </md>
                <p>Thus there is a function <m>g</m> such that <m>f(x,y)=g\!\left(\dfrac{y}{x}\right)</m>. Now set <m>y=vx</m>, so <m>y'=v+x\dfrac{dv}{dx}</m>. Substitution gives</p>
                <md>v+x\frac{dv}{dx}=g(v),</md>
                <p>hence</p>
                <md>x\frac{dv}{dx}=g(v)-v.</md>
                <p>This is separable:</p>
                <md>\frac{dv}{g(v)-v}=\frac{dx}{x}.</md>
                </li>

                <li>
                <p>From <m>P(x,y)\,dx+Q(x,y)\,dy=0</m> we have</p>
                <md>\frac{dy}{dx}=-\frac{P(x,y)}{Q(x,y)}.</md>
                <p>If <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are both homogeneous of degree <m>n</m>, then</p>
                <md>
                    -\frac{P(tx,ty)}{Q(tx,ty)}
                    =-\frac{t^nP(x,y)}{t^nQ(x,y)}
                    =-\frac{P(x,y)}{Q(x,y)},
                </md>
                <p>so <m>-P/Q</m> is homogeneous of degree <m>0</m>, hence depends only on <m>y/x</m>. Therefore the equation is homogeneous in the sense of parts (a)–(c), and the substitution <m>y=vx</m> transforms it into a separable equation as in part (c).</p>
                </li>

                <li>
                <p>Rewrite the equation as</p>
                <md>y'=\frac{2y^2-x^2}{x^2}=2\left(\frac{y}{x}\right)^2-1,</md>
                <p>which is homogeneous. Let <m>y=vx</m>, so <m>y'=v+x\dfrac{dv}{dx}</m>. Then</p>
                <md>v+x\frac{dv}{dx}=2v^2-1,</md>
                <p>so</p>
                <md>x\frac{dv}{dx}=2v^2-v-1=(2v+1)(v-1).</md>
                <p>Separate and integrate:</p>
                <md>
                    \int \frac{dv}{(2v+1)(v-1)}=\int \frac{dx}{x}.
                </md>
                <p>Using partial fractions,
                    <m>\dfrac{1}{(2v+1)(v-1)}=\dfrac{1/3}{v-1}-\dfrac{2/3}{2v+1}</m>, so</p>
                <md>
                    \frac{1}{3}\ln|v-1|-\frac{1}{3}\ln|2v+1|=\ln|x|+C.
                </md>
                <p>Thus</p>
                <md>\ln\left|\frac{v-1}{2v+1}\right|=3\ln|x|+C,</md>
                <p>or <m>\dfrac{v-1}{2v+1}=Cx^3</m>. Solving for <m>v</m> and substituting <m>v=\dfrac{y}{x}</m> gives</p>
                <md>
                    y=x\frac{1+Cx^3}{1-2Cx^3}.
                </md>
                </li>

                <li>
                <p>First simplify:</p>
                <md>
                    y'=\frac{2y^4+x^4}{xy^3}=\frac{2y}{x}+\frac{x^3}{y^3},
                </md>
                <p>which is homogeneous. Let <m>y=vx</m>, so <m>y'=v+x\dfrac{dv}{dx}</m> and <m>\dfrac{x^3}{y^3}=\dfrac{1}{v^3}</m>. Then</p>
                <md>
                    v+x\frac{dv}{dx}=2v+\frac{1}{v^3},
                </md>
                <p>hence</p>
                <md>x\frac{dv}{dx}=v+\frac{1}{v^3}=\frac{v^4+1}{v^3}.</md>
                <p>Separate and integrate:</p>
                <md>
                    \int \frac{v^3}{v^4+1}\,dv=\int \frac{dx}{x}.
                </md>
                <p>Since <m>\dfrac{d}{dv}(v^4+1)=4v^3</m>, we obtain</p>
                <md>
                    \frac{1}{4}\ln|v^4+1|=\ln|x|+C.
                </md>
                <p>Therefore <m>v^4+1=Cx^4</m>. Substituting <m>v=\dfrac{y}{x}</m> yields the implicit general solution</p>
                <md>
                    \left(\frac{y}{x}\right)^4+1=Cx^4
                    \quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
                    y^4+x^4=Cx^8.
                </md>
                </li>
            </ol>
</solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Mr.<nbsp/>Ratchett, an elderly American, was found murdered in his train compartment on the Orient Express at 7 AM. When his body was discovered, the famous detective Hercule Poirot noted that Ratchett had a body temperature of 28 degrees. The body had cooled to a temperature of 27 degrees one hour later. If the normal temperature of a human being is 37 degrees and the air temperature in the train is 22 degrees, estimate the time of Ratchett's death using Newton's Law of Cooling.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution component="instructors">
            <p>By Newton’s Law of Cooling, the body temperature satisfies
            <md>T(t)=T_a+(T(0)-T_a)e^{-kt},</md>
            where <m>T_a=22</m> is the ambient (air) temperature and <m>k&gt;0</m> is a constant.  Let <m>t=0</m> correspond to 7 AM, when the body was discovered and <m>T(0)=28</m>.  One hour later <m>T(1)=27</m>, so
            <md>27-22=(28-22)e^{-k}\quad\Rightarrow\quad 5=6e^{-k}\quad\Rightarrow\quad e^{-k}=\frac{5}{6},</md>
            hence
            <md>k=\ln\!\left(\frac{6}{5}\right).</md>
            Let <m>t_d</m> be the number of hours between Ratchett’s death and 7 AM.  At death the body temperature was normal, <m>37</m>, so
            <md>28-22=(37-22)e^{-kt_d}\quad\Rightarrow\quad 6=15e^{-kt_d}\quad\Rightarrow\quad e^{-kt_d}=\frac{2}{5}.</md>
            Therefore
            <md>t_d=\frac{\ln(5/2)}{\ln(6/5)}\approx 5.03\text{ hours}.</md>
            So Ratchett died about <m>5</m> hours before 7 AM, i.e. at approximately 2:00 AM.</p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>You are starting a new position, and your employer has a generous retirement plan.  If you put $500 a month into a 401(k) plan, your employer will match your contributions.  
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Assume that you are 25 years old and plan to retire at age 65, how large can you expect your 401(k) pension to be when you retire?  Assume that your 401(k) plan will collect interest at a rate of 5%.</p></li>

                        <li><p>If you begin withdrawing $60,000 every year at age 65, how long will your retirement fund last?</p></li>
                    </ol>

                    </p>
            </statement>
            <solution component="instructors">
            <p><b>(a)</b> Since you contribute $500 per month and your employer matches it, a total of $1000 per month is invested. 
            Let <m>r=\frac{0.05}{12}</m> be the monthly interest rate and 
            <m>n=40\cdot 12=480</m> the number of months from age 25 to 65. The future value of an ordinary annuity is
            <md>
                FV = P \frac{(1+r)^n-1}{r},
            </md>
            where <m>P=1000</m>. Thus
            <md>
                FV = 1000 \cdot \frac{(1+0.05/12)^{480}-1}{0.05/12}.
            </md>
            Since <m>(1+0.05/12)^{480}\approx 7.36</m>, we obtain
            <md>
                FV \approx 1000 \cdot \frac{7.36-1}{0.0041667}
                \approx 1.53\times 10^6.
            </md>
            You can expect approximately <m>$1.5</m> million at retirement.</p>

            <p><b>(b)</b> If you withdraw $60,000 per year and the fund continues earning 5% annually, then the annual interest earned on $1.53 million is
            <md>
                0.05(1.53\times 10^6)\approx 76,500.
            </md>
            Since the interest ($76,500) exceeds the withdrawal amount ($60,000), the principal will continue to grow rather than decrease. Therefore, at a 5% return, withdrawing $60,000 per year is sustainable indefinitely, and the retirement fund will not run out.</p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>


    </exercises>

    <subsection xml:id="firstlook02-subsection-sage">
        <title>Sage<mdash />Quick Start Guide to Solving Ordinary Differential Equations</title>
    
        <p><em>Sage</em> has powerful algorithms for finding exact and numerical solutions of differential equations. In addition, we can plot solutions and direction fields. Although some differential equations have an exact solution and can be solved using analytic techniques with calculus, many differential equations can only be solved using numerical techniques. This should not be too surprising if we consider how we solve polynomials. It is quite easy to find the roots of any equation of the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> by either factoring or using the quadratic equation, but solving an equation such as 
            <md>5x^7 - 6x^4 +3x^3 -23 x^2 +3x -17 = 0</md>
        is a much more difficult problem.  Unlike the situation for quadratic equations, there does not exist a general formula for solving seventh degree equations. We can even encounter difficulties when using a numerical method such as the Newton-Raphson algorithm.</p>

        <p>In general, <em>Sage</em> needs three things to solve a differential equation: 
            <ol>
                
                <li><p>An abstract function</p></li>
                
                <li><p>A differential equation</p></li> 
                
                <li><p>A <em>Sage</em> command to solve the equation.</p></li>
            
            </ol>
        Suppose we wish to solve the equation
            <md>\frac{dy}{dx} = x + y.</md>
        We can use the following sequence of <em>Sage</em> commands.</p>

        <sage>
            <input>
            y = function('y')(x)
            de = diff(y,x) == x + y
            solution = desolve(de, y)
            solution.show()
            </input>
            <output>
            -((x + 1)*e^(-x) - _C)*e^x
            </output>
        </sage>

       <p>The first command defines the abstract function. The second describes the actual differential equation. Finally, we use the Sage command <c>desolve</c> to find the actual solution. Try replacing the <c>solution.show()</c> command with <c>solution</c> or <c>latex(solution)</c>.</p>

       <p>We can also specify an initial condition for our differential equation, say <m>y(0) = 1</m>.</p>

        <sage>
            <input>
            y = function('y')(x)
            de = diff(y,x) == x + y
            solution = desolve(de, y, ics=[0,1])
            solution.show()
            </input>
            <output>
            h
            </output>
        </sage>

        <p>There are many other commands and packages to solve ordinary differential equations using Sage. For more information, see <url href="http://www.sagemath.org/doc/reference/calculus/sage/calculus/desolvers.html" visual="www.sagemath.org/doc/reference/calculus/sage/calculus/desolvers.html" />. An empty Sage cell is below for practice and exploration.</p>

        <sage>
            <input>
            </input>
            <output>
            </output>
        </sage>

    </subsection>
 
</section>

